[1] Bauchi state
Date: Mon 9 Nov 2020
Source: The Nation [edited]
https://thenationonlineng.net/yellow-fever-claims-eight-in-bauchi/


No fewer than 8 persons have died of probable cases of yellow fever in Ganjuwa Local Government Area of Bauchi state. There are 8 others who have also been placed under intensive care after contracting the disease.

Executive Chairman of the Bauchi State Primary Health Care Development Agency (BASPHCDA), Dr. Rilwanu Mohammed, disclosed these while briefing newsmen on Monday [9 Nov 2020].

Mohammed said the surveillance team of the agency made the discovery after taking samples of the 8 infected victims placed under intensive care. "Recently, mysterious deaths of people were reported in some villages in 2 wards of Ganjuwa LGA. Immediately our surveillance team moved in and took samples of infected victims and it was confirmed that they were yellow fever positive.

"This suspicion came from one of our supervisors who went to the local government for Polio immunisation and found out that some locals were having yellowness of the eyes and urine," he added.

There was occurrence of the disease last year [2019] where about 77 tested positive in Alkaleri, Bauchi, Toro, Ningi, Gamawa, Darazo and Warji local government areas.

[Byline: David Adenuga]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This report adds an additional state, Baushi, to the other 2 states where yellow fever (YF) cases are occurring. Bauchi state in the north of Nigeria is quite distant from Delta and Enugu states that are in the south. None of these states have adjoining borders and there is no obvious interconnectedness of their YF outbreaks. There is no indication in the above report that indicates the proportion of the population in Ganjuwa Local Government Area of Bauchi state that is vaccinated agains YF. - Mod.TY]

