******
[4]
Date: Fri 6 Nov 2020
Source: Premium Times [edited]
https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/424847-government-urges-calm-as-strange-disease-kills-dozens-in-enugu.html


The Enugu State Government, on Thursday [5 Nov 2020], confirmed many deaths from a yet unidentified disease in Ette Uno and Umuopu in Igbo-Eze North Local Government Area of the state. The 2 communities have recorded scores of deaths since September [2020] following the outbreak of the 'strange' disease.

A health officer in the area put the death toll at over 50, adding that specimens had been collected for proper diagnosis and treatment of other patients.

The disease, Premium Times learnt, broke out at Ette early September [2020] and spread to the border community of Umuopu, where 20 persons have died, including 4 on Wednesday [4 Nov 2020].

The source explained that the victims presented symptoms such as convulsion and diarrhoea before vomiting blood, adding that they are suspecting Lassa fever or cholera. "Between September and now, at least 37 persons have died in Ette. Also, Umuopu, which shares a common border with Ette, has recorded 20 deaths, 4 of which happened yesterday. It has been a strange development.

"The state Ministry of Health has been notified and investigations are currently ongoing to unravel the cause of the deaths. We have collected samples from the affected people and we are looking out for Lassa fever, cholera, yellow fever and meningitis. Coronavirus tests will equally start in the affected communities today. The state's Ministry of Health has brought an ambulance we are using to convey the sick ones to Enugu for proper diagnosis and treatment," the source, who pleaded anonymity because he is not authorised to speak to the media, said.

The source further said that a 30-year-old student of the University of Nigeria Nsukka, CO, 40-year-old EEO and 47-year-old SE were among the 20 casualties at Umuopu community

[Byeline: Joe Eze]

